<p><br>
<p><font color= "green">Textbooks:</font> 

  
<p>There are many textbooks covering special relativity.    Special
  relativity is also covered in many textbooks on classical mechanics
  or electrodynamics/electromagnetism, and often reviewed in some
  detail in the beginning of texts on general relativity or particle
  physics.  I list a selection below.

 
<p>Our library carries a number of these in paper copy and a few more
  as e-books.

<p>(I omit publisher and publication date; should be easy enough to find.)


<UL>

<p><li>Chapters 12 -- 14 of: 
&nbsp; &nbsp; 
Kleppner & Kolenkow, <I>Introduction to Mechanics</I>, 2nd ed. 

<br>
There are several copies of the book in the university library.  Very
pedagogical.  Covers the more elementary parts of this module.



<p><li>
Chapters 15 -- 17 of: 
&nbsp; &nbsp; <I>The Feynman Lectures on Physics</I>, Volume I

<br>A classic.  Free to read online, on <A href=
"http://www.feynmanlectures.info/"> this website</A>.


<p><li>
Chapter 1 of: 
&nbsp; &nbsp; Landau & Lifshitz, <I>The Classical Theory of
    Fields</I>
<br>This is Volume 2 of the famous `Course of Theoretical Physics'.  



<p><li>
Chapters 11 -- 14 of: 
&nbsp; &nbsp; 
Morin, <I>Introduction to Classical Mechanics</I>


<p><li>
The chapter on relativity in: 
&nbsp; &nbsp; Griffiths, <I>Introduction to Electrodynamics</I>
<br>
In the 2nd Edition this is Chapter 10, in the 4th Edition this is
Chapter 12.  


<p><li>
Chapter 7 of: 
&nbsp; &nbsp; Goldstein, <I>Classical Mechanics</I>
<br>
Concise treatment of some of the more advanced aspects. 
<br>
The chapter has been changed thoroughly between 2nd and 3rd editions. 
Perhaps use the 3rd edition where the notation is more modern. 

<p><li>
Chapters 1 -- 4 (and bits of chapters 5,6) of: 
&nbsp; &nbsp; 
Woodhouse, <I>Special Relativity</I>
<br>
More mathematical.  

<p><li>
Chapters 1 -- 5 of: 
&nbsp; &nbsp; 
Rindler, <I>Relativity: Special, General, and Cosmological</I>

<p><li>
Chapters 29 -- 34 of: 
&nbsp; &nbsp; 
Greiner, <I>Classical Mechanics: Point Particles and Relativity</I>

<p><li>
Bais, <I>Very Special Relativity: An Illustrated Guide</I>
<br>
A very special and worthwhile read.  Avoids formalism and teaches
through pictures (through a series of Minkowski diagrams). 

<p><li>Steane, <I>Relativity Made Relatively Easy</I>
<br>
Very pedagogical treatment at the level of this module. Covers
probably everything we are likely to do, and more.
    

<p><li>Nolting, <I>Theoretical Physics 4 - Special Theory of
Relativity</I>
<br>
Coverage at the level of this module, but does not cover everything we
will cover.


<p><li>Zee, <I>
Einstein Gravity in a Nutshell</I>
<br>
This book targets General Relativity, but on the way treats Special
Relativity in detail.  


</UL>


