<font color= "brown" size= +1>Continuous Assessment and the purpose of
  problem sets </font> 


<p>I plan to assign one problem set every week.  They will be posted  on this webpage.

<p>The assignments will be due on tuesdays at the beginning of the
  class at noon.  

  
<p>I will not be able to mark all the assignments; some assignments
  will go un-marked.  I will not announce beforehand which.  This
  means: it is in your advantage to work on each problem set, whether
  or not a particular one gets marked.

<p>Without working on each assignment set, you are
  likely to get lost quickly, as the module will build on the
  assignments and assume that you have learned the material you are
  supposed to learn through doing the assignments. 


<p>Assignment marks (`continuous assessment') will be counted toward
  the final module mark only if they are to the students' advantage.
<br>
(The policy is module-dependent and varies within the Mathematical
  Physics department.  In some modules, continuous assessment is
  `compulsory'.)


<p>The primary purpose of the problem sets is that they should help
  you learn the material at an optimal rate.  It will be assumed that
  you are attempting every problem set.  If you are comfortable doing
  all the problems during the week and then want to tackle additional
  problems, please let me know with a brief email and I will try to
  send you some further optional problems to work on.



